04028nam a22005175i 9780887553448DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062006xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808875534487 a10.1515/97808875534482doi  a(DE-B1597)664662  a(OCoLC)1408681634  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxcCA 4aBX8115.U77 2006 7aREL0430002bisacsh04a3221 aUrry, James, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMennonites, Politics, and Peoplehood :b1525 to 1980 /cJames Urry. 1aWinnipeg, Manitoba : bUniversity of Manitoba Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (300 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tThe Quiet in the Land -- tEurope -- tConfessions and Magistrates (1525-1790) -- tMandates and Privilegia (1650-1800) -- tRevolutions and Constitutions (1750-1874) -- tRussia -- tPower and Privilege (1790-1905) -- tConstitutionalism and Solidarity (1905-1918) -- tAutonomy and Ideology (1918-1929) -- tCanada -- tParty and Patronage! Manitoba (1890-1920) -- tCommunities and Identities: The Russländer (1923-1940) -- tParty and “Ethnicity”: Manitoba (1927-1974) -- tPolarization and Partisanship: Winnipeg (1921-1980) -- tThe Loud in the Land -- tEndnotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMennonites and their forebears are usually thought to be a people with little interest or involvement in politics. Mennonites, Politics, and Peoplehood reveals that since their early history, Mennonites have, in fact, been active participants in worldly politics. From western to eastern Europe and through different migrations to North America, James Urry’s meticulous research traces Mennonite links with kingdoms, empires, republics, and democratic nations in the context of peace, war, and revolution. He stresses a degree of Mennonite involvement in politics not previously discussed in literature, including Mennonite participation in constitutional reform and party politics, and shows the polarization of their political views from conservatism to liberalism and even revolutionary activities. Urry looks at the Mennonite reaction to politics and political events from the Reformation onwards and focusses particularly on those people who settled in Russia and their descendants who came to Manitoba. Using a wide variety of sources, Mennonites, Politics, and Peoplehood combines an inter-disciplinary approach to reveal that Mennonites, far from being the “Quiet in the Land,” have deep roots in politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Mennonite.2bisacsh1 aLoewen, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088755344840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780887553448423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780887553448/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles